iplomats, human rights organization, the United Nations, and other government and intergovernmental organizations. Professional historians of Yugoslavia, however, have been strangely silent about the wars and the breakup of the country. This book is an effort to end that silence. The goal of this volume is to bring together insights from a distinguished group of American and European scholars of Yugoslavia to add depth to our historical understanding of that country’s recent struggles. The first part of the volume examines the ways in which images of the Yugoslav past have shaped current understandings of the region. The second part deals more directly with the events of the recent past and also looks forward to some of the problems and future prospects for Yugoslavia’s successor states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aNationalismxBalkan Peninsula. 0aNationalismzBalkan Peninsula. 4aHistory -- European. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Baltic States.2bisacsh1 aBracewell, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCase, Holly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDjordjevich, Dušan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmert, Thomas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFine, John V. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJelavich, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrekić, Bariša, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaimark, Norman M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaimark, Norman M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRossos, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStokes, Gale, econtributor.